    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-27T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-27T04:00:00-05:00" n="1095"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1095">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/1371: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-27T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 27, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 28—7:40
                        p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1059. The Embassy has still been unable to obtain from the Foreign Office a copy
                    of the decree of April 19, 1943.<note n="47" xml:id="d1095fn1">The text of this
                        decree had not been published, and efforts to obtain a copy of it had not
                        been successful. Aron Naumovich Trainin wrote in his article in <hi
                            rend="italic">War and the Working Class</hi> for January 1, 1944, that
                        one of the purposes of this decree was to give to “Soviet courts an
                        appropriate weapon for the immediate struggle with the Hitlerite
                        criminals.”</note> Department’s 308, February 15, Embassy’s 550, February
                    18, 4 p.m.<note n="48" xml:id="d1095fn2">Neither printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>An article in <hi rend="italic">Freies Deutschland</hi>
                    <note n="49" xml:id="d1095fn3">The periodical of the “Free Germany” National
                        Committee founded in Moscow under Soviet auspices on July 21, 1943;
                        regarding early activities of the Committee, see <ref
                            target="frus1943v03#pg_552">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, pp. 552</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1943v03#pg_580">580</ref>, <hi rend="italic">passim</hi>,
                        and <ref target="frus1943v03#pg_602">pp. 602</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1943v03#pg_605">605</ref>.</note> for December 19, 1943,
                    concerning the Kharkov trial however includes the following statement: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Death by hanging was first introduced in the Soviet Union through a
                            decree of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet dated April 19, 1943. A
                            death sentence by hanging was first imposed last summer in the <pb
                                facs="1217" n="1207" xml:id="pg_1207"/> ‘Krasnipingdar [<hi
                                rend="italic">Krasnodar</hi>] trial’ (in the matter of atrocities
                            committed in the city and district of Krasnipingdar [<hi rend="italic"
                                >Krasnodar</hi>] during its occupation by the German army) and for
                            the second time in the recent Kharkov trial.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>A microfilm of this issue of <hi rend="italic">Freies Deutschlamd</hi> was
                    forwarded to the Department under cover of my despatch No. 229, March 3,
                        1944.<note n="50" xml:id="d1095fn4">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
